    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Salix alba are primarily derived from its bark, due to its high salicin content, a compound that is converted into salicylic acid in the body, similar to aspirin. Salix infusion, also known as willow bark tea, is made by steeping the bark in hot water, releasing its bioactive compounds, including salicin. White willow bark tincture and white willow tincture are liquid extracts of the bark, standardized to contain a specific amount of salicin, often used for pain relief and inflammation. Salix ointment is a topical preparation made by infusing the bark in a carrier oil, which is applied directly to the skin to relieve pain and reduce inflammation. These preparations are used to take advantage of the analgesic, anti-inflammatory, and anti-pyretic properties of Salix alba, which have been extensively documented in traditional medicine and modern research.",
